\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 Article #1
\f1\b0 : What Makes a Good Instructor?\
\
Over the past forty-something years, I\'92ve had the opportunity to train with numerous instructors - fifty-one to be exact. On the teaching side of things, some were excellent. Some were OK. And some were horrible. On the moral and ethical side of things, some were outstanding while other had question marks above their activities. Allow me to share with you my perspective on what I believe makes a good instructor.\
\

\f0\b For starters, a good instructor is an individual who cares his or her students
\f1\b0 . This, I believe, is the most important quality a good instructor can possess. To care for their students, a good instructor pays attention to the needs of all of his or her students, not just the talented ones, or the gifted ones, or the good looking, or the ones who are similar in gender, race, age, ethnicity, or interest. By consistently demonstrating a concern for the individual needs of each student, instructors will begin to develop a loyal following from many of their students.\

\f0\b \
\
\
Second, a good instructor is a giver.
\f1\b0  From my perspective, giving and caring go hand-in-hand. An instructor who truly cares about the progress of each student will consistently give from the heart. This instructor will graciously share his or her time, experience, wisdom and knowledge with all who need and desire them. Additionally, good instructors will consistently go above and beyond the call of duty. They will consistently give until they can give no more.\
\

\f0\b Third, a good instructor will have the ability to adapt his or her teachings.
\f1\b0  Because of a broad base of knowledge and experience, an adept instructor will know how to present the information he or she possess to a diverse group of students. Whether they are teaching to men or women, adults or kids, military or civilians, foreigners or locals, good instructors will know (or be able to figure out) the best way to present their style to the group they are in front of so that the information can be efficiently understood, digested, practiced and retained. They will know which subjects to present at the appropriate time, as well as which ones should be avoided. The good instructor will also make every effort to present information in an educative, entertaining and enjoyable fashion. This will help the students retain the information easier. It will also help the students develop a bond with their instructor.\
\
If an aspiring instructor does not know how to effectively present information to a diverse group of individuals, he or she should make every effort to learn how to do it. A good instructor knows that no one is born a phenomenal instructor. They understand that becoming one is something that takes time, effort, patience, focus, diligence and persistence. In other words, becoming a good instructor is a skill set that can be developed over time!\
\

\f0\b Next, a good instructor willingly adapts to the ever-changing needs of his or her students
\f1\b0 . The good instructor has paid attention to detail for years. He or she knows that students train for a variety of different reasons. Some students train for fun, while others train to relieve stress. Some train because they want to learn self-defense, while others do so because they desire to feel the adrenaline rush of competition or the euphoria of learning something new and challenging. Some students train because psychologically they still have something to prove, while others come to class because they desire to \'93feel\'94 a part of something bigger than themselves. The good instructor knows all of these things and adapts to them. He allows each student to find his or her chosen path. He also allows the students to change their choice of paths at a later point in time. Knowing how to adapt to each student is important part of the success and health of the training facility 
\f2\i and
\f1\i0  the instructor.\
\
Unfortunately, change and adaptation are two things some instructors fight as though their lives depended on it. Their refusal to change sends a subtle message to all who pay attention. It tells everyone who is watching or listening, \'93
\f2\i I have no desire to remain a student. I have all the answers.
\f1\i0  I know it all.\'94 It also implies, \'93I enjoy the instructor status and the power that I have.\'94 The good instructor knows that the needs of his or her students will change over time. They also knows that they must change and adapt to these changing needs, as well keep current on all the latest trends. This change will help bring new life into the training environment, as well as keep boredom and frustration at low levels.\
\

\f0\b A good instructor maintains a high level of awareness to those who have special needs
\f1\b0 : \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1) Those who learn very quickly.\
2) Those who learn at a slower pace.\
3) Those who lack confidence or need reassurance. \
4) Those who do not possess a high level of coordination. \
5) Those who still have something to prove to others and to themselves.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
The good instructor pays attention to the dynamics of each class. Good instructors know their students not only require them to be excellent instructors who share and care, but also that they will eventually want them to be the keepers of the peace, solvers of problems and judges of fairness and equality. In short, the good instructor makes every effort to stay keen about his or her students, as well as create and maintain a safe and enjoyable training environment for all.\
\

\f0\b Next, I believe a good instructor must have been a good student himself, since "it is impossible to lead if one has never truly followed".
\f1\b0  I believe it was Benjamin Franklin who spoke those words long ago, and they are still true today. In order to fully understand the needs of various students, the instructor must have first been an exemplary student: One who has learned his or her craft through hands-on experience, followed the examples given by senior students and instructors, made adjustments along the way for his or her own personality and body type, and then assumed more responsibility as it was given to him or her.\
\
I believe the good student has the potential to become a good instructor. I also believe the opposite is true, and that the not-so-good student has the potential to become a not-so-good instructor. Now, I am not saying that a not-so-good student could not become a good instructor. I just know that people tend to be creatures of habit. If they have taken short cuts as students, they will more than likely do the same thing as instructors. \
\
Additionally, I believe the really good instructors will always remain students. They will retain that child-like curiosity for martial arts, learning, and life. They will also be on the lookout for more efficient ways to teach, present, practice, and perform.\
\

\f0\b Finally, I believe the good instructor must make the effort to become and remain a kind, considerate and compassionate human being.
\f1\b0  Joking, or talking, negatively about students behind their backs or sharing confidential details with one student about another student are just a few examples of deeds that cause division and harsh feelings. The good instructor will lead by example. He or she will allow his or her actions to speak the intent and content of the heart. He or she will make every effort to keep his or her words and deeds above reproach.\
\
I hope that this article has been helpful and enlightening. It was written from the heart.\
\
\
\

\f0\b Article #2
\f1\b0 : Effectiveness, Efficiency and Playfulness: Part One
\f0\b \

\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 I have been involved in martial arts since 1981. In the early days, my main focus was practicality and self-defense. As soon as I had gained a certain amount of proficiency with what I had learned, I wanted more. I walked down the path of technical accumulation, like many do, and found that it led to a series of plateaus. So I began looking elsewhere.\
\
As I began to make efforts to define and refine my knowledge, I found that my initial concern in martial arts training was being effective with the knowledge I had gained. For many years after this discovery, I focused exclusively on being effective with the technical knowledge I had gained. Eventually, I became bored with effectiveness and began to search for something more lasting.\
\
Next, through a unique method of discovery I had discovered, I bumped into efficiency. I found through time and disciplined effort that efficiency enveloped, or contained, effectiveness. However, what made efficiency so addictive was the idea that I could make fewer movements, exert less effort and yet still accomplish the same goals. Once I got a taste of efficiency, I began focusing more of my training time on this area. While I had become more successful through the development of efficiency in many areas of Jiu Jitsu, I still sensed that something was missing.\
\
All of my training, all of my thinking, and all of my writings eventually led me to a final mindset. Here it is:\
\
With a certain amount of time training efficiency, I found myself moving towards a new concept that I would soon call "
\f0\b playfulness
\f1\b0 ." Playfulness encompasses the following:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\li360\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. A willingness to repeatedly place one\'92s self into vulnerable positions in order to obtain smoothness and finesse. Here\'92s an example: First, I train my escapes from the bottom of the side mount using posture and good hip movement. Then, I train my escapes without the use of posture. Next, I train my escapes without the use of hip movement. Finally, I train my escapes with minimal use of posture and a minimal use of hip movement. By the time I become proficient at this method of escaping, and once I put good posture and good hip movement back into the training, my escapes will be turbo-charged! Developing one\'92s skill sets to this level is imperative to being able to play. (
\f0\b NOTE
\f1\b0 : 
\f2\i This is something I did with side mount escapes. Some of you might remember reading in previous articles about my focus on side mount escape training for a period of seven years, yes? Well, this was how I was able to remain so focused on one topic for so long!
\f1\i0 )\
\
B. A high level of mastery in numerous related areas of Jiu Jitsu (
\f2\i e.g. butterfly guard control + half guard control + side mount escapes
\f1\i0 ). This is so important to developing one\'92s ability to play!\
\
C. A lack of a desire to finish my training partners with an explosive submission or hard strike. Instead, there was a growing desire to discover and explore the various levels of control, distancing and leverage. For example, I explored the differences between the following training methods: [1] 90% control and 80% control over an opponent\'92s body, [2] being on the bottom of the side mount position and analyzing the differences, as well as the pros and cons, between my opponent\'92s chest being ten inches away from my chest versus it being six inches away from my chest, [3] exploring the different amounts of leverage with a straight arm lock when attempting to finish it with the thumb up versus the thumb pointing to the left versus the thumb pointing to the right versus the thumb under my armpit, as well as wrist control versus thumb control versus hand control. This training led me to discover some of the very subtle differences between these various positions. It also led me to more fully understand control so I could play more often--especially with students who were stronger and had more endurance than I did. By exploring these differences, as well as gaining a massive amount of knowledge, I learned that I could be playful most of the time, reduce the amount and frequency of injuries and make sure all involved parties were having fun!\
\
D. The above training method led me to a mindset of a willingness and desire to allow others to enjoy the art at my expense. In other words, I could let people into the game, develop my timing, awareness and distancing while allowing my training partners to sweep and submit me! \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Having experienced effectiveness, efficiency and playfulness for many years, allow me to share with you some insights I have learned along the way:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\li560\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95 Effectiveness, while fun and exciting in the beginning, becomes boring after a while. To those who need to tap their students all of the time, it doesn\'92t become boring, but to those who desire to allow the next generation of practitioners a chance to experience success over and over again, effectiveness is boring.\
\'95 Effectiveness involves injuries along the way-- because if the tap is all you focus on, then speed, power and explosiveness become king. And when those elements are present, injuries are lurking around the corner!\
\'95 Effectiveness can sometimes be heavy and negative-- especially when a person is a white belt or an older student who is just beginning their journey in Jiu Jitsu.\
\'95 Effectiveness is generally self-centered and self-serving.\
\
\'95 Efficiency is a fascinating journey for the experienced and the mature.\
\'95 Efficiency involves fewer injuries than effectiveness.\
\'95 Efficiency is much lighter on the emotions, and on the attitudes.\
\'95 Efficiency still involves being effective, but it is not the main focus.\
\
\'95 Playfulness never gets boring.\
\'95 Playfulness rarely involves ego-based injuries.\
\'95 Playfulness is light and jovial. It is very easy on the emotions.\
\'95 Playfulness is very communal. It makes room for the next generation!\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
My goal in sharing this with you is to encourage you to one day seek out playfulness. Unfortunately, you need a series of skill sets to do this, and this skill set usually doesn\'92t present itself until mid to high purple belt. However, it is obtainable by all.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 Playfulness is so much more advanced than efficiency or effectiveness. Nevertheless, to even reach this level, the practitioner must go through hundreds of hours of effectiveness training and hundreds of hours of efficiency training.\
\
In part two of this article, I will go into greater details on effectiveness, efficiency and playfulness.\
\
Until then, enjoy yourself in this marvelous and fascinating art we call Jiu Jitsu!\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
\

\f0\b Article #3
\f1\b0 : Defining the Terms
\f0\b \

\f1\b0 \
Over the years, many of you have read and heard instructors use the following terms:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Basic\
2. Intermediate\
3. Advanced\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
I believe most Jiu Jitsu students have heard of or read these terms before. I also believe most of these students have glossed over them without ever taking the time to define what they really mean. \
\
If you were like many students (and instructors), you probably applied the terms something like this: \'93Basic\'94 for white belts and \'93Advanced\'94 for blue belts and above. \
\
In this article, allow me to share with you my definitions are for these terms.\
\
When I say or write the word \'93basic,\'94 I am referring to something that is primary and necessary for growth. For example, a basic attribute for all students of the standing arts is balance. Without balance, a student has no foundation to build off of. A basic technique for all students of the standing arts is a rear hand straight punch. So, regardless of whether a person is training in Boxing or Karate, that student must train his or her balance while performing a rear hand straight punch. Balance is also a primary attribute for all Jiu Jitsu students. And, a basic technique for all Jiu Jitsu students would be the hip escaping technique from the bottom of the side mount position.\
\
When I say or write the word \'93intermediate,\'94 I am referring to a phase of training that follows the basics. This phase of training is less focused on the learning of technique but is rather more focused on the employment of various training methods. These training methods are used to develop specific physical attributes like power, explosiveness, endurance, accuracy, etc. These training methods are also focused on developing mental attributes like focus, concentration, determination and pain tolerance. With the combination of clean and precise technique mixed with solid physical and mental attributes, the practitioner will have a marked advantage over an untrained individual who is bigger and stronger.\
\
Finally, when I say or write the word \'93advanced,\'94 I am referring to a phase of training that follows the intermediate level. This phase of training is much more complex than the basic phase. It focuses on these six areas:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Community\
2. Modification\
3. Adaptation\
4. Tactics\
5. Strategy\
6. Personalization\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
From my perspective, the first thing that should be obvious about an advanced practitioner is not his or her technique. Rather, it should be his or her willingness to give back and share with others. In other words, the advanced practitioner concerns himself or herself with community. They teach and share their chosen art because they love sharing and because they desire to give back.\
\
What comes next is advanced practitioners learn to modify techniques for themselves as well as for other student who train with them. In my own journey, the people who taught me the most about teaching were the students who were physically challenged. For example, my first group of blind students taught me how visual my teaching language and verbiage was. These students encouraged me to speak as though everyone in the room had their eyes closed. By doing this, I learned to modify my teachings for those who were in front of me. And by doing this, I became a better instructor over time. \
\
Additionally, I\'92ve had students who trained with me and could not lift their hips up and off of the mats more than an inch. Trying to teach them how to do a spinning arm lock from the guard was difficult at first because I did not know how to modify the techniques I had been taught to meet these students\'92 needs. Eventually, I figured out a way to modify this technique so that those with weak buttock and lower back muscles could perform the technique with the same effectiveness as others in the class.\
\
To make a long story short, learning how to modify techniques for personal needs as well as the needs of one\'92s students is an important part of the advanced students\'92 development.\
\
Adaptation is about making the effort to adapt one\'92s self to the unique set of circumstances that have presented themselves. This may sound like an easy task, but trust me when I say it is not. Let me give you an example:\
\
Let\'92s say you have to spar against several opponents, and let\'92s say your guard, with the gi, is the strongest aspect of your game. Your first opponent refuses to wear a gi. He sweats a lot and won\'92t allow you to wear a gi when you spar with him. Your second opponent is really good at passing the guard and holding down from the side mount. Your third opponent outweighs you by 45 pounds and is really good at leg locks. Your fourth and final opponent is a Division I wrestling champion who also happens to be a seasoned purple belt in Jiu Jitsu.\
\
Do you see how you won\'92t be able to use just one type of guard on your different opponents? Do you see how you\'92ll have to be proficient with the use of the closed guard, spider guard, butterfly guard, half guard, side mount escapes and various other related techniques and positions? Your Jiu Jitsu is going to have to adapt to each opponent. \
\
Next comes the use of tactics. I think of tactics as \'93tricks\'94 used to fool an opponent into thinking you\'92re going one way when in fact you are going in a different direction. For example, for years, I used the Kimura technique not as a finishing technique, but rather as a tactic to get on top of training partners who were much larger and stronger than I was. When I would entangle their arms, I would purposely let them pass my guard while grabbing a hold of their shorts or gi pants to prevent me from finishing the lock on the shoulder. However, just as soon as they were settling in on their position, I reversed them and put them on their back. This tactic worked very well for many years. \
\
Next, there\'92s strategy. Strategy is nothing more than a group of tactics designed to give the advanced practitioner marked advantage over time. For example, one strategy you could use to gain an advantage over your opponent would be to encourage him or her to become emotional during the match and try too hard to finish certain techniques. Knowing how good this opponent is, you may feel as though his or her skill sets in certain areas are so much better than yours that you purposely evoke emotions into the match or make yourself vulnerable so that the opponent tries really hard to finish you quickly. Then, when he or she tires before you do, you take advantage of and exploit this weakness. In other words, you use four or five tactics to cause your opponent to expend more energy than he or she should. Then, sensing the pace of the match starting to slow down, you engage him or her with more fervor and cause him or her to use even more energy. Still, you patiently wait for the appropriate time to begin your attack.\
\
Finally, there\'92s personalization. This is the part of the art where you personalize everything to work just for you. At this point in time, it doesn\'92t matter what techniques you choose; if it works for you then that is all that matters. For those who are instructors, they do the same thing for their advanced students.\
\
As you can see, the advanced game is so much more complex than the basic one.\
\
Having taught martial arts for twenty-seven years, I can tell you that a lot of beginner level students are intrigued by the advanced game and want to know more about it. Allow me to encourage all beginner level students, or those who wear a white or blue belt, to focus on the basics for the first three to five years of your journey in Jiu Jitsu. Don\'92t try to jump ahead to what you think or feel is \'93the good stuff.\'94 Pay your dues like the rest of us. Learn, practice, and develop some finesse in your basic techniques first. This effort will pay huge dividends in the end. And, if you try and take shortcuts, trust me, it will show itself down the road!\
\
I hope this article has been enlightening and that it gives you a better idea of what to focus on at the different belt and experience levels. \
\
\

\f0\b Article #4
\f1\b0 : Intermediate Level Brazilian Jiu Jitsu\
\
Below is an excerpt from an article I shared with the instructors in my association many years ago. Enjoy!\
\
Here are ten areas to train for intermediate level Jiu Jitsu (
\f2\i once the basics have been trained
\f1\i0  extensively):\
\
1. Take an inventory and review what you think you know:\
\
	A. How many basic techniques do you know from each position?\
	B. How well do you know and understand these basic techniques?\
	C. Can you perform them effectively in a dynamic environment?\
	D. How much energy do you use when you perform the techniques? \
	E. Can you perform them equally on both sides of your body?\
	F. How well do you know your mechanics? Can you list each movement?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li1440\partightenfactor0
\cf0 *Answering these questions will help determine your current and true strengths, weaknesses and tendencies. They will also show you where you need to focus your training.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
2. Put your basics together into two and three technique combinations:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. Can you perform these combinations smoothly (without any jerky movements)?\
B. Can you perform these combinations slowly (without feeling the need to speed up)?\
C. Can you perform these combinations smoothly and slowly with your eyes closed?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 *Answering these questions will help you to develop awareness, sensitivity, efficiency and finesse. With a high level of awareness, sensitivity, efficiency and finesse, you are setting the table for the next part of your journey - Advanced Jiu Jitsu!\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
3. Put the basics together into two and three technique combinations 
\f0\b based on positioning
\f1\b0 . This is the next phase of combination training. This is where one technique overlaps another technique mechanically. Make sure you pay attention to the entire process of the combination, not just the ending. Take notice of how the ending of technique \'93A\'94 no longer ends where it used to end.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * The purpose of this training is to go through the process of \'93shedding\'94 / becoming more efficient in your movements. When two techniques are put together into a combination, there are three moving parts: Technique A, Technique B and the transition between techniques A and B. All three of these must be trained individually and then collectively. Additionally, when Technique A and B are put together into a combination you will find that Technique A is much shorter than when it is used / practiced / performed by itself.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
4. Put the basics together into simple two and three technique combinations 
\f0\b based on resistance
\f1\b0 . Define resistance (
\f2\i six lines of movement
\f1\i0 ). Learn and practice the techniques for the most common forms of resistance. Focus only on basic techniques.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * The purpose of this training is to develop your awareness, sensitivity and flow. An important point here about training resistance: Over the years, I have seen students make the mistake of learning a new technique, practicing it a few times and then asking their training partners to resist the newly learned technique. This, in my opinion, is a horrible mistake. It\'92s a mistake for a few important reasons. First, the student has just learned the technique. So, asking another student to resist only makes the matter more complicated-- and no skills will be developed with this mindset. Second, the form of resistance is not defined. Here\'92s an example: You put me into an arm lock and then you tell me to resist. I bite you in the leg and then you become upset with me. You have no right to become upset with me because you didn\'92t define the resistance. All you said was, \'93OK, now resist.\'94 So, I resisted in a manner that was guaranteed to make you think and act differently about the arm lock. This is why resistance training is reserved for intermediate level students. Resistance must be defined first in order to learn how to effectively neutralize it.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
5. Learn, practice and develop one or two counters to the following techniques:\
\
	A. The bridge and roll mount escape\
	B. The basic elbow/knee mount escape\
	C. The foot lift mount escape\
	D. The foot drag mount escape\
	E. The basic under the leg guard pass\
	F. The basic over the leg guard pass\
	G. The basic replace into the guard side mount escape\
	H. The basic go to your knees side mount escape\
	I.  Mount posture\
	J.  Side mount posture\
	K. Guard posture\
	L. Straight arm lock\
	M. Bent arm lock\
	N. Rear choke\
	O. Guillotine choke\
	P. Triangle choke with the arms\
	Q. Triangle choke with the legs\
	R. Palm up, palm up collar choke\
	S. Palm up, palm down collar choke\
	T. Straight foot lock\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 U. Heel hook\
V. Figure-four toe hold\
W. Knee bar\
X. Scissors sweep\
Y. Foot lift sweep\
Z. Knee sweep\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
By learning, practicing and developing these counters, you will not only raise your level of awareness to self and your training partners, but you will also develop a highly polished intermediate level Jiu Jitsu game.\
\
\
6. Refine and polish what you know. Make your basics better, more efficient and smoother. Let me give you an example: \
\
When you perform a basic sweep, how much effort do you put into making it successful? Let\'92s say your answer is 80%. In other words, when you attempt a basic sweep from your guard while sparring, it takes you 80% speed and power to make it happen. OK. That\'92s a good starting point, but I hope you can see that you have a lot of room for improvement.\
\
In order to become more efficient, you\'92ll need to train basic sweep much more in order to make it smooth and efficient (
\f2\i e.g. move down the scale and using just 60% effort
\f1\i0 ). Do you know how to train the sweep to become more efficient? If you replied, \'93Well, I just need to do more repetitions\'94, you would be correct. But with that answer, I would ask you a few important follow up questions like, \'93How would you train these repetitions? What would be your mindset while training? And how will you know when you\'92ve reached your goal?\'94 If you were like most students, you\'92d probably stand there with a blank look on your face-- not knowing exactly what to say. \
\
I write this because I have seen a lot of students, in numerous countries around the world, train technique (
\f2\i i.e. they do a bunch of repetitions
\f1\i0 ) and then they spar. They have no structured or progressive training methods to lead them from the knowledge and understanding of a technique to having a useable and repeatable skill set on the mat. If you do not know how to do this, then that is your next goal. Learn how to accomplish this with a structured and progressive training method. If you\'92re not sure on how to do this, I will be producing an iOS App on this in the coming months. Please keep your eyes on my main website {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.RoyHarris.com"}}{\fldrslt \ul www.RoyHarris.com}} for more information\
\
7. Positioning your body to purposely funnel an opponent\'92s efforts down a specific path:\
\
	A. From mount (
\f2\i turn on side, bottom knee up and out
\f1\i0 )\
	B. From guard (
\f2\i hands on ground, fingers pointed back towards your feet
\f1\i0 )\
	C. From side mount (
\f2\i push opponent\'92s head alongside your body
\f1\i0 )\
\
By developing your positional skills to a high level, you force your opponents to move in predictable manners. For example, when you learn how to properly position yourself on the bottom of the side mount position - like I taught on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/roy-harris-bjj-over-40/id426984931?ls=1&mt=8"}}{\fldrslt \ul my BJJ over 40 app}} - you force your opponents to give up chest to chest or scarf holds and go to either the north and south or knee on the belly positions. So, by developing proper positioning as well as the timing of this position, you can usually be one step ahead of your training partners-- because you know where he or she is going to reposition their body when they pass your guard and reach the side mount position!\
\
Why does this positioning work? It works because it takes away those things that are primary to their control. I will share more on this topic in another article.\
\
\
8. Develop your sense of timing:\
\
There are three points in time in when you can employ a technique:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Beginning            Middle        	End\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	____________________________
\f0\b X
\f1\b0 ____  (Beginning level students)\
	________________
\f0\b X
\f1\b0 ________________  (Intermediate level students)\
	___
\f0\b X
\f1\b0 _____________________________  (Advanced level students)\
\
Take the time to identify the various movements within your techniques. This will heighten your awareness. Then, move your response to the stimuli back on the timeline until you reach the beginning.\
\
Please remember that timing is faster than speed, more powerful than power and stronger than strength. \
\
\
9. Making the effort to master the primary positional aspect of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu:\
\
	A. Mount escapes\
	B. Side mount escapes\
	C. Guard control\
	D. Guard passing\
	E. Side mount dominance\
	F. Mount dominance\
\
For white and blue belts, I recommend they focus on just four positions: (1) The top of the guard, (2) the bottom of the guard, (3) the top of the side mount and (4) the bottom of the side mount. These four positions are the primary positions of their belt level. For purple belts, I\'92d recommend adding the top and bottom aspects of the mount position. Being able to escape from the inferior positions and control from the top positions is paramount to laying a solid foundation in the art!\
\
10. The process of mastery:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. Knowledge\
B. Understanding\
C. Familiarity\
D. Confidence\
E. Mastery\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Knowledge begins the process. At this level, we take in new information at the ears and/or eyes and then pass it on to our brain.\
\
Understanding is the next step in the process. When we move from a general knowledge to understanding, we make the conscious choice to tie this new piece of information to an older and more familiar piece of information. Once we do this, we have a general understanding of the new piece of information, and, it is now tied to our memory.\
\
Familiarization comes next. When we make a conscious and disciplined effort to make the new information an integral part of our conscious and subconscious mind, it\'92s only a matter of time before we are intimately familiar with it.\
\
Now, before I move on, it is important that you understand two important points. First, knowledge and understanding occur within the mind. Also, knowledge and understanding, generally, happen within the first few minutes of explanation, demonstration, and practice. Second, familiarity implies something mental as well as something emotional. Within the context of martial arts, it also implies a ton of practice because the student now knows what the new technique 
\f2\i feels
\f1\i0  like.\
\
Confidence is the next step. At this level, the student now has a few useable, repeatable skill sets. Because of these skill sets, the student has a level of confidence in the performance of the techniques he or she never had before. This is where Jiu Jitsu becomes fun!\
\
The final step in the process is mastery. At this level, the student has now mastered a handful of related techniques, which means the student is highly proficient with four to five techniques from a given position and the student is also proficient at two or three technique variations.\
\
The equation looks something like this:\
\
Joe is quite proficient at the employment of techniques 1, 2, 3 and 4. These four techniques are \'93high-percentage\'94 techniques. However, he is also very proficient at techniques 1a, 1b, 1c, 2a, 2b, 2c, 3a, 3b, 3c, 4a, 4b and 4c. This means that Joe's arsenal is a force to be reckoned with. He is highly proficient at sixteen related techniques from a specific position.\
\
This is how I want you, as my instructors, to train.\
\
You have already been through the basic level course. This intermediate level course will be a longer journey than the basic one, but it promises to be more fun.\
\
Enjoy!\
\
\
