\f0\b Article #6
\f1\b0 : An Overview of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu Basics\
\
Since the main issue in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu is control, you must first learn how to prevent an opponent from controlling your body by developing the proper skill sets to effectively and efficiently escape off of your back from the mount and side mount positions. This is primary to developing a really good Jiu Jitsu game. I write this because I have seen black belts have a difficult time escaping from the front mount position - one of the easiest positions from which to escape!\
\
Secondly, you must learn how to control your opponent\'92s body through the use of major and minor control positions. The primary major controls positions are the front mount, back mount, side mount and guard positions. The primary minor control positions are the triangle choke with the legs, the straight-arm lock, the Kimura, the Americana and the guillotine choke. (
\f2\i More on these in another article and app
\f1\i0 )\
\
Third, you must develop the following seven (7) physical attributes:\
\
	1. Awareness\
	2. Balance\
	3. Coordination\
	4. Timing\
	5. Sensitivity\
	6. Explosiveness\
	7. Endurance\
\
By focusing your training on the above-mentioned areas, you will lay a solid foundation upon which you can build something that is personal and something that will last.\
\
Here is a list of twenty-eight techniques that I believe will help you to develop a set of useable, repeatable skill sets that you\'92ll be able to use in your 40\'92s, 50\'92s, 60\'92s and early 70\'92s:\
\
I. MOUNT ESCAPES\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. Two techniques on each side\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 		1. Bridge and roll technique\
		2. Elbow/knee technique\
\
II. SIDEMOUNT ESCAPES\
	A. Two techniques on each side\
		1. Place into the guard\
		2. Go to your knees\
\
III. GUARD CONTROL\
	A. Two techniques on each side\
		1. Closed guard control\
		2. Spider guard control\
\
IV. GUARD PASSING\
