\f0\b Article #7
\f1\b0 : Legwork in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu
\f0\b \

\f1\b0 \
When it comes to controlling an opponent inside your guard, you must have a mixture of flexibility, good leg movement and sensitivity. Here are the twelve movements themselves to help develop good leg movement:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Circles with the feet, inward and outward\
2. Circles with the knees, inward and outward\
3. Pushing motions with the soles of the feet\
4. Pushing motions with the shins\
5. Pushing motions with the calves\
6. Pushing motions with four sides of the knee\
7. Pushing motions with the thighs\
8. Hooking motions with the insteps\
9. Pulling motions with the calves\
10. Pulling motions with the top of the knee\
11. Grabbing motions with the bend of the knee\
12. Driving and grabbing motions with the top of the hip\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Once the student learns the movements, understands the movements and becomes thoroughly familiar with these movements, it will only be a matter of time before this familiarity turns into confidence.\
\
What comes next is sensitivity training. In order to do this, close your eyes when you train. Learn to feel with your legs. Close your eyes when you spar. Gain a sense of timing in real time. Make yourself more vulnerable, more often. In other words, let people get close to passing your guard before replacing the guard or going to your knees.\
\
The various elements I have written about so far only deal with control. There has been no mention of sweeps or submissions, and there is a specific reason for that. In the beginning of students' journeys in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu (from white belt to purple belt), most of their time should be spent learning how to control an opponent from their guard rather than learning how to submit or sweep. Why? With the element of control, the student can buy time to look for or set up a sweep or submission. Without control, the student is forced to use speed and/or explosiveness to effect a sweep or submission.\
\
Now that you have been armed with this knowledge, are you going to practice your guard control? Are you going to focus on it for an extended period of time? I hope so!\
\
Guard control is one of the more important fundamental skills in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. Its importance cannot be overlooked.\
\
Enjoy the journey!\
\
\
