\f0\b Article #8
\f1\b0 : Quantify Your Grappling Experience, Part Two\
\
Some time ago, I wrote an article entitled, \'93Quantify Your Grappling Experience.\'94 In that article, I listed 120 areas of grappling training that I had explored over several years. These areas of training represent the foundation of my grappling experience. My purpose in writing that article was to show you the process I went through to become a competent grappling instructor and black belt in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. I also wanted to give you an example of how to quantify your own grappling experience, as well as encourage you to obtain more depth with your current knowledge of grappling.\
\
In this article, I would like to expand on the first one and show you the depth of my training in each of those 120 different areas of grappling training.\
\
The individual components of training that I am about to share with you are components that I felt were critical to my development as an instructor and as a practitioner of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. The individual components of my training are:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Technical knowledge\
2. Mechanics\
3. Precise limb placement\
4. Combinations and drills: the use of momentum\
5. Attributes\
6. Angles of pressure\
7. Limitations of technique\
8. Areas of vulnerability\
9. Counters\
10. Control\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Each of these components should be applied to the one120 areas of grappling training that I listed in the previous article. Let\'92s take a look each component:\
\

\f0\b Technical knowledge
\f1\b0 : How many techniques do I know to escape from the mounted position? Well, when I first started, I knew nothing. However, my knowledge has grown from one technique to now over 40 (forty-two to be precise). Now that\'92s 42 different techniques for escaping the mount position. I know this seems like a lot of information, but wait until you read the rest of this post. Technical knowledge is only the beginning!\
\
Learning and discovering new techniques is an important part of process of becoming skilled. However, learning techniques is not the most important part. I have seen a lot of students get caught up in trying to accumulate new techniques, when all they need to become skilled was right in front of them. \
\
Technical knowledge will teach you what to do in a specific situation. However, that\'92s all it will do. Technical knowledge does not and will never equal a skill. Knowing how to do a technique is not the same as being able to perform it reflexively under pressure. Technical knowledge is a good place to start, but your training methods must progress much further. Knowing a technique is also not the same as fully understanding it or being able to confidently teach it to a wide variety of students from varying cultures and backgrounds. Anyone can show someone else a cool technique. However, the real question is whether or not the instructor has the ability to break down the information into small edible pieces so that even a child could understand what is being said. Another question is whether or not the instructor has the ability to link this new information with other known information, and if he or she can teach principles, concepts and guidelines that lay the foundation for technical knowledge.  Now that we know that technical knowledge is a good starting place, let\'92s move on.\
\

\f0\b Mechanics
\f1\b0 : Mechanics are the individual components of a technique that give leverage over an opponent\'92s body. For example, the individual components that make up the mechanics of the triangle choke with the legs are:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Back of right thigh on left shoulder\
2. Bend of right knee on neck\
3. Grab your right shin with left hand\
4. Left forearm presses against the right side of the opponent\'92s cheek\
5. Squeeze left knee inward towards opponent body, and up towards your own chest\
6. Right arm hugs opponent\'92s left thigh and spins your body & shin perpendicular to spine\
7. Top of right calf presses into back of opponent\'92s neck\
8. The right heel is pulled equal to or in front of the opponent\'92s right shoulder\
9. The bend of left knee goes over your right lower leg\
10. The toes on your right foot point upward\
11. Both heels are pulled to your buttocks\
12. Both knees are squeezed together\
13. Ensure that the opponent\'92s chin is above the inside of your right thigh\
14. Raise your hips up towards the ceiling\
15. Both knees are pushed away from your belly\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
As you can see, the total numbers of components in this simple technique is fifteen. Imagine putting the triangle into combination with an arm lock! You would have at least twenty-four different movements going on at roughly the same time. Do you see how complex two technique combinations are when you take a look at the individual components of each technique? Imagine putting four or five techniques together into one combination. (I
\f2\i  
\f1\i0 spent two years working on my triangle choke, so I understand how complex this subject is.)\
\
With correct mechanics, I rarely get to step fifteen. Most people tap around step seven or eight. Correct mechanics gives me the leverage I need to effectively and efficiently apply this technique. Learning the mechanics of each technique is crucial to developing a skill. If I do not employ good mechanics with my techniques, I will be forced to use speed, strength and explosiveness to compensate for my lack of skill.\
\

\f0\b Precise limb placement
\f1\b0 : Good grappling boils down to two things: pushing and pulling motions. Where you place your limbs will determine how much effort you will spend trying to accomplish your objectives. For example, if my opponent was trying to stay mounted on top of me, and I was about to perform an elbow/knee escape on my left side, where should I place my right elbow?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. On his stomach.\
B. On my stomach.\
C. On his ribs.\
D. Against his left hipbone.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
The correct answer would be D, because this is where I will have the most leverage to push against his body. If I push on his stomach, it will give because the stomach is soft. If I push on his ribs, I expose my arm to an arm lock. Yes, I can accomplish the same objective by pushing on the other areas, but I will leave myself open for attack, and I will end up expending more energy in the process.\
\
Precise limb placement will give me the leverage I need to apply the least amount of force to accomplish my goal. Precise limb placement is very closely related to mechanics.\
\

\f0\b Combinations and drills
\f1\b0 : By putting the basic techniques together into various combinations, the student will build a solid repertoire of variables for future grappling matches. Some combos will feel natural at first, while others will feel unnatural, even after lengthy hours of practice. Some combinations are more practical for fighting than others, while others are used strictly for the development of physical attributes like coordination and timing.\
\
Drills link techniques together into logical combinations. What I mean by \'93logical combinations\'94 is that there are certain techniques that naturally lead into other techniques. These logical combinations should be practiced first because they are easier to grasp.\
\
Drills also help to develop attributes specific to the techniques you are trying to employ. For example, if you were trying to develop the attribute of sensitivity, the best drills would be ones that required you to grapple cooperatively and not competitively with your training partners for extended periods of time with your eyes closed. By learning how to feel your training partners' movements and intentions, you can then learn to move with them and not fight against them.\
\
The employment of drills and combinations also helps prepare the student for the use and creation of momentum. For example, when an opponent begins to move his or her weight from left to right, it would be best to follow that movement by pushing or pulling it to the right and allowing the pressure or energy to continue on its original path.\
\
Here is an example of a simple combination:\
\
Person A is mounted on top of Person B.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Person B performs the Upa (bridge and roll) technique on his left side and is successful in his escape.\
2. Person A flows into a spinning arm lock on the opponent\'92s left arm as soon as his back hits the ground.\
3. Person B flows into a knee lock on the opponent\'92s left knee to escape and counter the spinning arm lock.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Drills and combinations are the fundamental training tools that experienced grapplers use to defeat much larger and stronger opponents because they help the practitioner to link information together.\
\

\f0\b Attributes
\f1\b0 : Attributes are those qualities that fuel your techniques. Techniques without attributes are nothing more than flowery movements. Attributes like speed, power, timing, spatial relationship, balance, strength, endurance, flexibility, accuracy, pain tolerance, perceptual awareness, emotional control, sensitivity, explosiveness, coordination and body mechanics give life and vibrancy to your techniques. They make your techniques come alive. They also make people respect them.\
\
Developing attributes specific to the techniques you are employing is crucial to becoming skilled in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. For example, to escape the mount position, the main attributes you need are timing, sensitivity and strength. You need good timing because if you push at the wrong time, you will expend more energy than you need to escape the position, which in turn will mean that you will tire sooner. Good timing is the sense you develop to know when it is the appropriate time to do a specific technique.\
\
Sensitivity gives you the ability to sense your opponent\'92s intentions and move with him or her, instead of against him or her.\
\
You also need a certain amount of strength to be able to push on certain areas of his or her body to get your opponent to move where and when you want him or her to move. These areas include the shoulders, the triceps, and the upper and lower back. You must train these muscles at the specific angles in order to become effective with your pushing motions.\
\
Attributes are an important part of your training program and must not be overlooked. Pure technique rarely wins.\
\

\f0\b Angles of pressure
\f1\b0 : The angle at which you apply pressure, regardless of whether it is a pulling or pushing motion, determines the efficiency and effectiveness of the movement. For example, if your opponent is mounted on top of you, and you turn onto your left side to perform elbow/knee escape, at which angle do you push with your right elbow?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A. Directly over your head\
B. Up towards the ceiling over your left shoulder\
C. Down towards your left hip\
D. Directly to your left\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
The correct answer is B, because your hips will be moving in that direction first (
\f2\i the first component of the mechanics of an elbow/knee escape is to raise your hips up off of the ground
\f1\i0 ). Therefore, your right elbow must continue the lifting motion of your hips to further elevate them because the main objective of the escape is to create more space between your hips and the opponent\'92s hips.\
\
Knowing which angle to apply pressure to is very important in lowering the amount of energy you expend to accomplish specific goals. Every move you do in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu involves pushing or pulling the opponent\'92s body at specific angles. If you know the specific angles to apply pressure, your ability to accomplish your objectives will be much easier. \
\
I know that this is a lot of information, but it is very important to learn!\
\

\f0\b Limitations of each technique
\f1\b0 : When you practice your techniques, you must understand that each technique is limited by distance, window of opportunity, current skill level, body type and personality. A technique is limited by distance because of the length of a person\'92s limbs and the space between your body and your opponent's body. For example, it would be difficult to do a spinning arm lock from the guard if your opponent\'92s chest was pressing against your chest. It would also be difficult if the opponent was standing up in your guard and his or her head was far away from you and his or her hands were on your hips. If his chest were pressing against yours, there would not be enough space to perform the arm lock. If her head and arms were far away from you, there would be too much space. Range plays a major part in determining which techniques are viable and which ones are not.\
\
The windows of opportunity also limit techniques. Sometimes, the window of opportunity is so small that to attempt a specific technique would be difficult. For example, if you were grappling an opponent who was smaller, much faster and more experienced than you, it would be very difficult to attempt a spinning arm lock on him from your guard, because your window of opportunity would be so small that your chances of success would be very low. He or she would be much smaller and faster than you are, and more experienced than you. What would be better for you is to attempt an arm lock when you are on top of him or her, say from the mount position. This way, you could use your weight to limit his or her mobility. Plus, your window of opportunity would be much larger.\
\
Current skill levels also play into the equation. Repeatedly sweeping or submitting an equally skilled opponent rarely happens. Doing the same thing on a higher skilled opponent is not likely either. \
\
I know this sound like common sense, but you would be surprised at how many people ask me to teach them how to tap a higher belt. Once, I had a guy who told me the following: \'93I am having problems getting the arm lock on this one guy in my class. He seems to always know when it is coming. What can I do to get him into the arm lock and make him tap? I\'92ve tried what you showed me the last time but it didn\'92t work.\'94 When I asked him the color of his training partner\'92s belt, he told me it was purple. Now, mind you, this student was a white belt with less than six months of experience. He somehow thought that all he had to do was take three or four private lessons from me and he\'92d learn all that he needed to know in order to make a purple belt - someone with ten times his experience - tap! I know he was sincere in his intentions, but he did not understand that experience and skill mean a lot in this sport. I explained this to him on two separate occasions, but he still thought he could somehow cheat the system and get that purple belt to tap.\
\
Additionally, an opponent\'92s current skill level will determine which strategies and techniques you will be able to utilize.\
\
Body types also play a major role in determining which techniques are more suitable for you than others. For example, several years ago I sparred with a guy who was 5\'928" and weighed 350 lbs. He saw me grapple a bunch of guys at a seminar and put all of them in the triangle choke with the legs. He told me that he wanted me to teach him how to do the same thing. I told him that because of his body type - more specifically the thickness of his thighs - he would not be able to do what I did. I also told him how the triangle was a handmade technique for people with long and skinny legs, and that it would be better for him to learn to use his weight on the mount and side mount positions. The thickness and length of his legs would prevent him from ever obtaining a triangle on most students, especially those students with thick necks and/or thick chests.\
\
Your body type will determine which techniques feel more comfortable for you. Also, your body type will determine how you apply certain techniques. For example, students around the world have varying forearm length. Some students have very long forearms because they are very tall while others have short forearms. This makes it impossible to teach the paintbrush and kimura techniques the same to every student. Some will have to grab higher on the opponent\'92s forearm than others. Body type not only determines which techniques are more suitable for a specific body type, but it also determines how they are applied.\
\
Certain techniques are more suitable for certain personalities. Some people are naturally aggressive, while others tend to be passive. Those who are aggressive tend to prefer to be on top of their opponents, while those who are passive don\'92t mind being on their back and working their techniques from that position. Also, chokes, headlocks and neck cranks tend to be the choice of more aggressive students in the beginning. The aggressive personalities tend to push the envelope. They try to create opportunities, whereas the softer, more passive personalities are content with waiting for an opportunity to present itself.\
\

\f0\b Areas of vulnerability
\f1\b0 : Every technique has an area of vulnerability, or an area that is weak to an attack and can be exploited. For example, when you attempt a triangle choke on your opponent from your guard, there is a short period of time where you are susceptible to having your guard passed. This short period of time occurs during the transition from uncrossing your ankles to the precise placement of your legs for the triangle. Understanding the areas of vulnerability for each technique will help you in the long run, especially when it comes to counters.\
\
By taking the time to identify the areas of vulnerability for each technique, you can then begin to practice a series of combinations that expose you to the least amount of vulnerabilities.\
\

\f0\b Counters
\f1\b0 : What is a counter? A counter is a movement that prevents an opponent from accomplishing specific goals. It\'92s an area that most grapplers want to train right away because they do not like tapping to or being controlled by their opponent. The depth at which a person knows counters depends heavily upon his or her current skill level. Most beginners do not know any counters. Those who have been practicing grappling for years know several counters.\
\
However, the real question is how deep your knowledge of counters extends. Let me show you something that will pique your curiosity. Here is \'93passing the guard\'94 broken down into small components (defined objectives):\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Base and posture\
2. Uncross the ankles\
3. Monitor the hip\
4. Pass under, over or around the legs\
5. Place your weight on the opponent\'92s upper torso\
6. Anchor your weight on the opponent\'92s upper torso\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Let\'92s focus on the fifth objective, \'93placing the weight on the opponent\'92s upper torso.\'94 A very common question I am asked by students is, \'93If I am on my back and my opponent is trying to pass my guard, how do I counter his attempt to place his weight on my chest?\'94 Simple: by pushing with your hands on the major chokes points of the body: the head, the shoulders, the hips and the knees. By pushing on these points, you will gain leverage over your opponent\'92s body and be able to create enough space to place him back into your guard. This is counter number one.\
\
The next obvious question is, \'93How can my opponent counter my pushing motions?\'94 Simple: by changing the angles at which he or she applies pressure. If you are pushing up against his or her shoulders and your opponent twists his or her body to the left and to the right, your hands will slip off of the shoulders and go floating off into outer space. Your opponent's weight will fall on top of your chest and he or she will have successfully countered your counter. This is counter number two.\
\
The next obvious question is, \'93How do I counter that?\'94 Simple: by changing the pushing motions from your wrists to your elbows. This is counter number three. \
\
We can keep going on and on and on with these counters. The next question will put us four counters deep. \
\
So where does this counter thing end? It doesn\'92t. It just keeps going on into infinity.\
\
However, what may shock you is this: 
\f2\i Counters always lead back to the basic techniques
\f1\i0 .
\f0\b \

\f1\b0 \

\f0\b Control
\f1\b0 : The last component I want to share with you is control. There are five levels of control:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Full control in your favor\
2. Partial control in your favor (51% or more)\
3. 50% / 50% control by each contestant\
4. Partial control in the opponent\'92s favor (51% or more)\
5. Full control in the opponent\'92s favor\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Grappling matches where two contestants are equally matched spend most of their time in levels two, three and four. Rarely does one contestant have full control over his or her opponent for an extended period of time. Since most of the time in grappling matches is spent with partial control and 50/50 control, much of your training time should focus on these three areas.\
\
The most common positions that contestants find themselves in are the half guard or half mount position. I think the difference between these two positions depends entirely on who has more control. If the person on the bottom has more control, then it should be called the half guard position. If the person on top has more control, then it should be called the half mount position.\
\
The focus of your training at first should be to learn how to prevent someone from controlling you (positional escapes) and then learning how to control the opponent (positional dominance).\
\
I also believe that there is another issue regarding control, and that has to do with learning how to control your emotions. Even if your opponent is mounted on top of you and you are tired, you should be in control of your emotions and not panic. You must remind yourself that all you need is to buy a little time to collect your thoughts and regain your composure. Then you can begin to mount your escape.\
\
Staying in control of your emotions is an important component of training regimen. It should also be an important part of your life!\
\
One last comment about control: good posture allows you to retain a certain amount of control in an inferior position. Good posture will make it possible for you to escape from that inferior position with ease and finesse.\
\

\f0\b Conclusion
\f1\b0 \
\
In this article, I listed ten different training components that I thought were important in my personal development. I hope they gave you a good idea of the process I went through to become a competent instructor and black belt in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu.\
\
I challenge you to quantify your own grappling experience and then identify as well as strengthen the weak areas of your grappling game. I hope this article will make a positive impact on your knowledge of grappling, and I hope you enjoyed reading it, because I enjoyed writing it!\
\
\
\

\f0\b Article #9
\f1\b0 : From White to Black Belt\
\
Allow me to share my observations of the progression through the five belt levels of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. I believe this will help you to understand where you are now and where your journey will lead you in the months and years to come.\
\

\f0\b White Belt\
\

\f1\b0 Plain and simple: at the white belt level, you learn the basics, lay a solid foundation, and you pay your dues. In a nutshell, you\'92ll spend a lot of time on your back. You also end up being the student who does most of the tapping. Keep heart, though; no one is born an expert. \
\
During this period of time, you\'92ll be learning and developing your basics. These basics will not only lay a strong foundation for you, but they will also help you progress through the middle ranks more smoothly. In my day, I\'92ve seen many purple and brown belts that took shortcuts in their white belt days, and this showed itself on the mat. I\'92ve experienced purple belts with phenomenal guards, but then when their guard gets passed, their side mount and front mount escapes look horrible. So, don\'92t try to overlook or by-pass your basics. You\'92ll need them in the years to come.\
\
Now, your ability to grapple successfully as a white belt will largely depend upon previous martial arts experience (a Judo or Wrestling background help a lot), your current fitness level (a high level of fitness helps a lot), your willingness to be disciplined in your training and your ability to learn visually (visual learners adapt and absorb information more quickly).\
\
Students with a wrestling background seem to adapt very well to the similar, but vastly different, grappling methods of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. Those with an athletic background also adapt quite well. Those with a striking background sometimes have a difficult time adapting. The reason is they are usually accustomed to visually grabbing onto the vertical and horizontal lines of walls, doorways, etc., to stabilize themselves, and they feel uncomfortable with the diagonal lines of grappling. They quickly learn that the ground is not as familiar, and that they need time to acquaint themselves with this new perspective.\
\
The most frustrating part about being a white belt is the fact that most of the advanced students will make you tap several times, or at least dominate you in the various positions. I remember feeling this frustration quite well. This frustration usually leads to questions such as, \'93How do I get on top of these guys? How do I escape the side or full mount? How do I tap out the blue and purple belts?\'94 Unfortunately, there\'92s nothing you can do besides getting used to being tapped out and dominated in the various positions. Consider tapping as a form of learning, and a method of paying your dues. As a white belt, I remember feeling like a rag doll in the hands of purple bets. Still, there was nothing I could do about it then. Brazilian Jiu Jitsu is just one of those \'93time in service\'94 endeavors. A person simply has to put in their time. There are no short cuts!\
\
There is encouraging news, though. Blue belts had to go through this stage too, and look at them now! \
\
So keep training. Very soon, you will be one of the blue belts who are tapping out the other white belts in class. And, as you keep training, you\'92ll eventually be able to escape from any position with finesse and ease. Then it will be your turn to watch the frustration of the new white belts. It will also be your turn to encourage them as I have encouraged you.\
\
One final comment:\
\
White belts are expected to rely on speed, power, strength and explosiveness to perform. After all, that is all they know. However, once you don the blue belt, the world of Jiu Jitsu is supposed to change for you, and for your training partners.\
\

\f0\b Blue Belt\

\f1\b0 The blue belt is the belt of basics and survival. Here you focus on escaping from most of the inferior positions, like the mount, the guard, the side mount, the wrestler\'92s cradle and headlock positions. Being able to escape from these inferior positions is paramount to being able to dominate from superior positions as well as make your opponents tap. Additionally, these escapes are a vital component in laying a strong foundation in grappling. \
\
When you, as a blue belt, can easily escape the tightest pin from just about anyone at your academy, you will find yourself on top more. And when you find yourself on top more often, you will have more opportunities for submission. However, you shouldn\'92t jump into submissions too soon because you haven\'92t yet developed the skill to hold someone down with finesse and ease. I have seen too many blue belts rush into submissions, only to become frustrated because they can\'92t finish them. Consequently, the blue belt continuously seeks to learn more submission techniques, thinking that the \'93new\'94 and \'93sneaky\'94 techniques will make them more skilled. Such blue belts don\'92t realize that their inability to finish their opponent is related to their inability to control and dominate their opponents. Naturally, the blue belt feels good to have escaped a hold down and land on top. However, they also feel that they have only one shot at sinking in the submission. The blue belt knows if he fails, he will end up on his back, so he usually stalls, waiting for the opponent to make a mistake.\
\
Once you have a firm grip on positional escapes, you should progress to positional dominance, or the ability to control an opponent.  When you can easily escape from most of the inferior positions with finesse, I recommend taking some time to focus on learning how to control your opponent with greater ease and finesse. Anyone can control her or his opponent by using all of her or his strength for short periods. However, it takes time to develop the skill sets of being able to efficiently hold down an opponent-- especially when they are tired. Take your time and train this area right!\
\
Once you have a good grip on positional escapes and dominance, you can begin to develop a few good submissions. However, try not to become so consumed with them, especially since there are several more areas to train.  Therefore, you can\'92t afford to spend too much time on submissions. Yes, I know that submissions are the more enjoyable part of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. I am not saying that you should not train in them. I am simply saying, \'93Don\'92t focus on them quite yet. Save some of the fun for when you are a purple belt!\'94\
\
As a mid-level blue belt, you may have a large repertoire of positional and submission techniques. However, your depth of knowledge will still be limited due to your experience level. Due to this limitation, you will still require a good amount of speed, power, and explosiveness to affect your techniques. This is to be expected. \
\
Another interesting thing that happens at the blue belt level is that the bar of performance is raised to highly competitive levels.  When I was a white belt, it felt OK to tap to everyone since I was only a white belt. However, once I was promoted to blue belt, many of the bigger, stronger and more talented white belts began to set their cross hairs on me. Many of my once-fellow white belt sojourners wanted the privilege of being able to say, \'93I made a blue belt tap!\'94 It seemed as if overnight the game had become very competitive. That is what made it so interesting, though.\
\
If you think the game sounds interesting at the blue belt level, wait until you hear about the coveted purple belt level.\
\

\f0\b Purple Belt\
\

\f1\b0 The purple belt is the belt of finding and developing momentum and the use of combinations. At this level, the amount of energy you expend to accomplish a specific task should be considerably lower than it used to be. Your game should have a certain amount of grace and finesse to it. In other words, you should not have to rely on speed, power and explosiveness to get you into or out of positions. Your repertoire of techniques should be very high, since at the white and blue belt levels you accumulated a wide array of techniques. At the purple belt stage you will therefore focus on acquiring a deeper level of knowledge as well as the refining and polishing of your techniques. \
\
Now that you\'92re a purple belt, you will start to do things you wished you could do when you were a white belt. In this exciting stage of training you will put the basic techniques together into various two and three-technique combinations, and you will begin to use of momentum. As you gain experience in these areas, you will use these combinations and momentum more and more. And the more you use them, the less you will need speed, power and explosiveness to perform your techniques. \
\
To focus on using momentum, you must train your entire body to read, feel and follow pressure. Up until this point, most things in your Jiu Jitsu training have been visual. But now you have to try and develop a high level of physical sensitivity. Then, you will begin to flow with your opponent and not force techniques with speed and power. Being able to use momentum to flow with your opponent helps when you are grappling training partners who are much bigger and stronger than you. Pushing an opponent\'92s dead weight around is exhausting if you do not have a firm foundation in escapes and positioning. You will need to use the momentum that your opponent gives you as well as create your own momentum when your opponent is not in motion. By utilizing momentum, you will need less strength to perform your techniques and accomplish your goals.\
\
Your purple belt training should also involve tying the basic techniques together into two, three and perhaps five technique combinations. Note I said \'93basic\'94 techniques. The purple belt mentality is very different from the white and blue belt mentality. White and blue belts think the answer to all difficulties is learning more techniques. But the purple belt thinks, \'93I need to refine the techniques I know and then learn how to reflexively put the appropriate techniques together into flowing combinations.\'94 \
\
For example, when I learned the triangle, I thought it was just a matter of throwing my legs over my opponent\'92s head and shoulder and then squeezing my legs together. As I matured in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu, I noticed that there was a specific set of components that made up the technique. And I noticed that these components could in turn be broken down into sub-categories. Now as a black belt, the triangle is a myriad of over 20 different and subtle moving parts that must be put together in a specific order so they can work together towards one goal: applying pressure to the neck. Once I had mastered the triangle, I put it together with other basic techniques, such as the arm lock, the hip bump sweep, the kimura, the twisting wrist lock, the figure four foot lock and the knee lock. Knowing how to combine the triangle with other basic techniques was very important to my development. Once I could combine these techniques and use them with momentum, I felt ready to take on the world and you will, too. Numerous students at my seminars, my school and other schools have said they feel the same way. \
\
In other words, as the purple belt\'92s base of knowledge and experience continues to widen, he or she will gain more and more confidence. Therefore, it is no surprise that highly charged matches occur at this stage, especially among the new purple belts. Why? It is this way because just like the white belts wanted to make the blue belts tap, some of these \'93veteran\'94 blue belts want to make a purple belt tap. In addition, some purple belts go through a period that I call \'93testing their wares\'94. They want to see how they compare to the older, more experienced purple belts, especially those who are about to be promoted to brown belt.\
\
One more area that I feel purple belts should begin to learn, practice and develop is their ability teach this phenomenal art to others. From my perspective, this is a missing area within Jiu Jitsu. I see a ton of very talented practitioners out there, but I don\'92t see the same quantity of adept instructors. \
\
Face-to-face teaching is both a science and an art. The science part is fairly straightforward: Place the seven elements of highly effective communication into your presentation each time you present (
\f2\i Ponder, organize, condense and clarify what you want to communicate; take the available time into consideration; always consider the person or persons with whom you will be communicating before you open your mouth; take the teaching environment into consideration; present your thoughts and ideas; watch your audience, while speaking, to ensure they are following and understanding what you are presenting; review and/or ask questions at the end of your presentation to ensure the audience understood what you just shared with them. In other words, seek feedback to ensure your presentation was clear and on point.
\f1\i0 ) The artistic part of teaching is much more complex because the instructor must possess a heightened sense of awareness to self, others, and the environment, simultaneously. And, this artistic part of teaching involves knowledge and understanding of, as well as a familiarity and confidence with, culture, gender, group dynamics, safety, psychology and a host of other considerations. (
\f2\i FYI, this is something I teach in all of my instructor courses-- be they Brazilian Jiu Jitsu, Jeet Kune Do, Filipino Martial Arts or Grappling. It is also something I present when I am mentoring someone.
\f1\i0 )\
\
So, for all current purple belts reading this article - as well as you senior blue belts - I encourage you to take some time and learn how to effectively communicate this art. You will need it when you become a black belt. You may even need it now to help your instructor teach classes.\
\

\f0\b Brown Belt\
\

\f1\b0 This is the belt of mastery of most of the basic techniques. It is also time to develop something I\'92ll call \'93at-will grappling\'94. Submissions play a big part in brown belt training. For example, when I decide someone is ready for a brown belt, I tell the student that he or she is nine months to twelve months away from a brown belt. Then I give him or her a schedule of tasks to focus on in their training. \
\
Before becoming a brown belt, the purple belt must be develop and train a handful of escapes from every position. I expect brown belts to be able to escape every position both with 
\f2\i and
\f1\i0  without the use of their hands. They must know how to push and pull as well as lift and lower with every portion of their anatomy. I want them to be able to hold other students down both with 
\f2\i and
\f1\i0  without their hands. I want them to use all of the basic techniques in three and five technique combinations. I also expect them to begin refining their submissions. This is where my \'93at-will grappling\'94 training method comes into the picture. I will tell the student, \'93For the next sixty days, all I want you to do is apply straight arm locks when you grapple with the other students. No chokes or leg locks, just arm locks.\'94 Then, once they have completed this journey, I will tell the student, \'93For the two months, all I want you to do are leg locks.\'94 After they have completed this journey, I will tell him or her to focus on chokes for the next couple of month. Thus the student has been able to practice, and refine, one task for an extended period of time. Because they tell the other students that all they are going to do is arm lock them today, their opponents know what the purple belt is going for. This forces the purple belt to be creative in setting up the submission. Since setting up an opponent is a difficult task, I introduce it at the advanced purple belt level. (
\f2\i Even though the lower belt levels yearn to learn it, they are not really ready for this kind of training.
\f1\i0 )\
\
Once the student is pretty good at arm locks, leg locks and the choke, I narrow the scope of his or her training. Next the student will focus on one specific limb. I will say, \'93For the next month, all I want you to do is arm lock your opponent\'92s left arm.\'94 This mandate forces the student to develop a multiplicity of ways to enter into the straight-arm lock on the left arm. However, the student has the confidence to go for these submissions because she or he has a foundation in positional escapes and dominance. Without this foundation, the student would be reluctant to try it for fear of ending up on the bottom again. However, because the student with this foundation can easily escape from any position, and because the student can readily hold down and control his or her opponent, she or he can try for these submissions time after time. This is why I do not place a lot of emphasis on submissions until the purple or brown belt levels. Position and control are the most important tools to develop at first. \
\
Once a student has a mid-level of confidence with his or her basics, he or she is promoted to a brown belt. At this new level, the student must continue to refine his or her game, seeking out weak areas, focusing on and polish them. The student must also find and focus on his or her strengths for an extended time, since these will define the student's character as a black belt. Most black belts have a specialty. For example, some are good at throws, others at collar chokes. I happen to be good at leg locks. I want my brown belts to find a sweet spot and then train it like crazy.\
\

\f0\b Black Belt\
\

\f1\b0 This is the level in which you focus your training on polishing your basic techniques, the counters to these techniques as well as placing your personal signature on the art of Jiu Jitsu. What is your signature? It is your area of specialty. For example, some black belts like me develop an affinity for leg locks. Others focus on throws, takedowns, arm locks, or collar chokes. At the black belt stage, you 
\f2\i really
\f1\i0  begin to refine and redefine the art. Brazilian Jiu Jitsu becomes more personal. Students take advantage of the fact that there\'92s more than one way to skin a Jiu Jitsu cat. They also start to notice what does and does not work on certain types of training partners and act accordingly. \
\
But let me stop here for a moment. These things apply only to the black belt who is still refining, growing, learning and adapting. They do not apply to the black belt who is stuck in his or her ways, paralyzed by a resistance to change. \
\
To some degree, the learning process starts over again at the black belt level. If a new black belt is honest, he or she will realize how little he or she knows about this art. The black belt should also accept the fact that there is a HUGE difference between a new black belt and a veteran black belt who has ten years of consistent training after they were promoted to black belt. \
\
For example, since I have had a black belt for a few years, I am relatively new, or \'93a white belt amongst other black belts.\'94 But when you look at someone like Professor Royler Gracie, he\'92s had his black belt for several years before I even thought about training in Brazilian Jiu Jitsu. He has so many more tens of thousands of hours competing, teaching and training than I have, there\'92s no way to compare my black belt with his. As a new black belt, I am on a new journey, one just as long and hard as the one I had traveled to reach this point. \
\
At the black belt level, your technical expertise is high. Of course, you may not be able to skillfully perform all your technical knowledge as well as you\'92d like. You will have some favorite moves you like to use most of the time. However, over time, if you continue to train in all areas with the same intensity as you did for earlier belts, your skill level will continue to increase. The only difference is that your game will become much smaller. Rather than work on new techniques, you will polish and refine the old ones. You will work on small, subtle movements that will make the art much easier and more enjoyable.  You will make smaller movements to accomplish the same objectives as before! Let me give you an example:\
\
To a black belt, the difference between escaping an inferior position and being held down is often the difference between your hips moving one or two inches! The black belt\'92s feel and sensitivity of the game is much higher than the white, blue and even purple belt\'92s game. The black belt will begin to move like a shadow, flowing effortlessly around an opponent\'92s movement, following his or her path. The black belt will find the opponent\'92s weaknesses and then exploit them.\
\
Your knowledge and ability to execute counters will also be much higher. For example, when someone performs a basic technique, you will be three or four moves ahead of him or her. You will know that for every move, there are several counters, and for every counter, there are several more counters. Let me show this to you another way.\
\
Let\'92s call the bridge and roll escape from the mount (Upa) technique \'93A\'94. As shown below, technique \'93A\'94 has ten counters to it: \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A-1 		Straight-arm lock\
A-2 		Catch your balance with your head\
A-3 		Catch your balance with your right foot\
A-4		Catch your balance with you left foot\
A-5 		Catch your balance with your far arm\
A-6 		Spin to knee on stomach\
A-7		Spin to side mount\
A-8		Turn onto your side\
A-9  		Roll and sweep to mount \
A-10		Triangle choke with the arms\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Let\'92s now take A-1, the first counter (Straight arm lock) to technique \'93A\'94 bridge and roll escape from the mount). A-1 also has ten counters, as shown:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A-1.1		Heel hook\
A-1.2 		Sit up and crush escape\
A-1.3		Sit up and crush escape to knee lock\
A-1.4		Sit up and remove leg off face\
A-1.5		Sit up and spin to opposite side\
A-1.6		Roll over shoulder escape\
A-1.7		Basic elbow/knee escape\
A-1.8		Basic elbow/knee escape, go to the back\
A-1.9		Basic elbow/knee escape\
A-1.10 	Shin lock \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
I could keep going on and on with counters. I could list the ten counters for A-2, A-3, and so on. Then I could list the counters for A-1.1, A-1.2, and so on.\
\
Do you see how long this training could go on for?\
\
I hope this article has helped you to understand the progression from white to black belt. The process of becoming skilled at Brazilian Jiu Jitsu is very fun, frustrating, time consuming and nerve racking. However, it is also very rewarding. There\'92s nothing like obtaining a useable, repeatable set of skills on the mat and being able to take them with you wherever you go.\
\
I wish you continued success in your journey. Keep training hard and smart!\
\
\
\

\f0\b Article #10
\f1\b0 : Grappling Instructor Manual Excerpt\
\
In the middle 1990\'92s, I began answering questions online about Brazilian Jiu Jitsu, Jeet Kune Do, self-defense and other martial arts related topics. In answering tons of questions, the idea of developing a structured progressive method of instruction for Jiu Jitsu kept coming up in conversation after conversation. Since I was powerless to affect the powers that be in the Jiu Jitsu world, I decided to do something about this missing piece of the puzzle. I decided to write a mini-manual and teach a basic grappling instructor\'92s course. I called it \'93The Apprentice Grappling Instructor Course\'94 for the following reasons:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 - I used the word \'93Apprentice\'94 because I wanted these instructors (and the general public) to understand that they were becoming a part of an apprenticeship program. While no one can make a competent instructor in a week or a weekend, I wanted the general public and the students who took the course to know that they were beginning a journey with me - because the word \'93Apprentice\'94 implies that a person is just beginning to learn the process.\
\
- I used the word \'93Grappling\'94 because I wanted to give credit to the styles of martial art, and their instructors, who had helped me become the grappler that I was. I disliked how the Brazilian Jiu Jitsu community on one hand was very critical of other styles of martial art, but on the other hand were training the leg locks of Sambo and the throws and takedowns of Judo and Wrestling - but yet they were still calling their style \'93Brazilian Jiu Jitsu.\'94 So, to give credit where credit was due, I used the word grappling because Brazilian Jiu Jitsu did not train leg locks, throws, takedown or holds in the 1990\'92s. So, in my grappling course, I gave credit to the styles that positively had impacted my method of grappling - specifically Brazilian Jiu Jitsu, Judo, Greco-Roman Wrestling, Freestyle Wrestling, Sambo, Dumog and Chin Na.\
\
- I used the words \'93Instructor Course\'94 because my courses are different from others. Instead of just teaching a bunch of techniques to the students, I wanted to teach them HOW to teach. In other words, I wanted them to know the science and art of effectively communicating their thoughts and ideas, how to control and influence group dynamics, different methods of effectively dealing with the myriad of problems that present themselves at an academy (
\f2\i e.g. hygiene / gender / money / attitude issues, problem students, etiquette, getting / keeping clients, teaching to various groups, understanding the unstated needs and demands of the clients, etc\'85
\f1\i0 ).\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Here is an excerpt from the manual:\
\
Now that you have completed the Apprentice Level Grappling Instructor Course, and have logged a handful of hours of the teaching and training the techniques you've learned, I'm sure this question has crossed your mind: "What's next?" \
\
Here is an overview of how I want you to train for the first few years as an instructor in my association:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. Develop good fundamental movements.\
2. Know, and more fully understand, the mechanics of your basic techniques.\
3. Practice your basic techniques to the point of reflex.\
4. Put the basics together into simple combinations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Now, let me go into further detail on each one of these.\
\
For starters, the basic techniques and training methods you've learned will help you lay a solid foundation in the grappling arts. These basics develop the fundamental movements of grappling. When I say fundamental movements, I am referring to core movements that are found in every technique. Let me give you a couple of examples of this: \
\
The bridge and roll escape from the mounted position is technique designed to help you develop high and powerful vertical hip movement. Without this kind of hip movement, your escapes will depend on the strength and endurance of your shoulders and upper arms. \
\
Additionally, the bridge and roll escape will help your offensive game. By developing a strong bridge, your ability to finish your submissions (
\f2\i i.e. straight arm locks, chokes and leg locks
\f1\i0 ) will become stronger.\
\
Here's another example: The elbow / knee escape from the side mount position. This technique is designed to help you develop and strengthen lateral hip movement. When an opponent can pin your hips down and keep them in one place, he or she will have an easier time holding you down from the side mount position. Good lateral hip movement is the key to being able to escape the mount and side mount positions. Additionally, lateral hip movement is an absolute requirement for being able to aggressively attack from the open guard position.\
\
Next, explain to your students the importance of [a] learning the proper mechanics of a technique, [b] practicing the technique to the point where they can do it perfect, each and every time, and then [c] developing the timing of the technique. Let your students know that "knowing" a technique is just the beginning. Now the hard work begins.\
\
Here is a brief list of techniques and the fundamental movements they need to develop:\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'95 Upa - posture and bridge and roll\
\'95 Elbow/knee (mount) - posture and lateral hip movement\
\'95 Under the leg guard pass - posture, proper head movement and base with movement\
\'95 Going to the knees - posture, proper hip movement and precise arm placement\
\'95 Headlock escape - posture, proper hip movement and precise arm placement\
\'95 Elbow/knee (side mount) - posture, lateral hip movement, push with knees\
\'95 Three chokes / three arm locks - body mechanics (use of the entire body to perform the choke or lock)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Second, I highly recommend you take a look at the individual components of each technique and determine the reason or reasons why you do what you do. It will help you to memorize the techniques as well as self-analyze why a particular technique is not working. Besides, sooner or later, one of your students is going to ask you why he should do a particular movement the way you told him to do it. \
\
For example, let's take a look at the Upa (bridge and roll) technique. A student might ask, "Why is it so important to trap the arm at the elbow and the wrist? Can't I just trap the arm anywhere on the forearm and still be effective with the technique?" Now, do you know the answer to this question off the top of your head? If you do, great! If you don\'92t, please go back to the beginning of this manual and review your mechanics.\
\
Let me ask you another question that a student might ask you, "Why is it important to raise my hips up as high as possible? Can't I just raise them up a little bit and push the guy over?" Again, do you know the answer? \
\
By digging deeper into the techniques and training methods you think you already know, you will make a lot of personal discoveries. Some of these personal discoveries will contradict your previous knowledge, and that\'92s OK. The goal is progress!\
\
What will you do when you discover a more efficient way of doing a technique? Will you throw out the old technique? If so, why? If not, why will you keep the old technique around? I do this in my teaching. There are some things I\'92ve kept around since my early days of training with the Gracie Brothers. I keep them around for a specific set of reasons. However, there are other things I have thrown out-- at least for myself--because they no longer work like they used to and because the world Jiu Jitsu has changed so much. Helio Gracie\'92s methods worked well for him in his day. But some of these methods no longer work like they used to-- because so much has changed.\
\
So, here are a handful of things to keep in mind as you teach: \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 1. \'93Old techniques\'94 are old techniques for you. \
2. New techniques are new for you. \
3. Inefficient techniques are inefficient techniques for you. \
4. What works for you does not necessarily work for each and every one of your students. \
5. What works for everyone else may not work for you. \
6. What is inefficient for others may be efficient for you. \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
In other words, everything is relative to one's own personal experience. This is very important for you to know and understand, because it will affect your students and it will also affect your business!\
\
My goal as your instructor is to "teach you how to fish" so that one day you can fish on your own and personalize your own fishing habits. It is not my intention to spoon-feed you a boneless fish each and every day. That would make you dependent upon me for every little thing. You are an individual. You have your own life. You have your own experiences. I am just a guide to your own personal development. By encouraging you to dig for yourself, as well as teaching you how to dig, I will help you to obtain the personal fulfillment of self-discovery.\
\
Encouraging you to dig deeper into what you already know is one way of getting you to intimately know your subject matter. Intimate knowledge of your subject matter is something students expect or demand of their instructors.\
\
Third, it is imperative that you practice these basics until you can perform them perfectly, every time, without thought. You must practice until your muscles memorize and feel them. The reason is simple: When combinations are introduced, if the basics are performed sloppily, the combination itself will be sloppy.\
\
Plus, when I introduce you to the concept of transitions (acknowledging, defining, controlling and manipulating them), if your basic techniques are sloppy or imprecise, you will not be able to fully grasp the concept of transitions because you will still be struggling with (and thinking about) the basic techniques. If you cannot define, control and manipulate transitions, you will not be able to use strategy to set up your opponent for a sweep, choke, or arm lock. As you can see, the basics lay a foundation for you to build off.\
\
Yes, I know that practicing the basics is boring. Yes, I know many of you think you already know them. However, I strongly suggest you continue practicing these basics. To this day, I continue to refine my basics, and I've been doing this stuff for many years. Just recently I have made some new discoveries about some of my basics. I've discovered a few more efficient methods for performing side mount escapes. I wish I knew this new stuff years ago because it would have helped me. If I can continue to practice and refine my basics, I think you should consider it as well.\
\
Thus far, I've talked about developing fundamental movements, digging deeper into your understanding of the basics, and then practicing and refining the basics. These three components lay a solid foundation for the intermediate level Jiu Jitsu.\
\
Before I move on to the next topic, I'd like to interject something here, something that I feel is very important as an instructor and as a lifelong student: Taking notes. Take lots and lots of notes. They will help you to remember techniques and training methods. They will also help you remember all of the subtle details that make the technique easier to perform. These notes will help you to remember the fine, subtle details that are lost with time. I personally have over 600 pages of notes I've taken over the past fourteen years. They help me to remember things I forgot years ago.\
\
Once you have a firm grasp on the basics, you can begin to put them together into simple two and three technique combinations. Once you can perform simple combinations, you should then move on to more complex three and five technique combinations.\
\
Once you can effortlessly put the basics techniques together into simple and complex combinations, you are primed and ready for the intermediate Jiu Jitsu level.\
\
The intermediate Jiu Jitsu level is more concept-based training than technique-based training. It makes you rethink your basics, as well as challenges you physically and mentally. The intermediate Jiu Jitsu level requires a firm understanding and proficiency with the basics. I will write more about this in another article.\
\
I hope this helps to secure your mindset on those areas that matter most!\
\
}